# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: davidian-revolution
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:davidian-revolution/a-a-m-duncan] From 1962 to 1993 he was Professor of Scottish History and Literature at the University of Glasgow.
[src:davidian-revolution/a-a-m-duncan] He was also President of the Scottish History Society, and edited the Scottish Historical Review from 1963 to 1970.
[src:davidian-revolution/a-a-m-duncan] On giving up his professorship, he became Clerk of Senate and Dean of Faculties, retiring from the university in 2000.
[src:davidian-revolution/a-a-m-duncan] From 2001 he was Emeritus Professor of Scottish History and Literature, but continued to publish on the history of Scotland in the Middle Ages.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:davidian-revolution/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] The **Office of the Advocate General for Scotland** is a ministerial department of the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] The position is currently occupied by Catherine Smith, Baroness Smith of Cluny.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office of Advocate General for Scotland was created in 1999 by the Scotland Act 1998 to be the chief legal adviser to the United Kingdom Government on Scots law.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] This function had previously been carried out by the Lord Advocate and Solicitor General for Scotland, who were transferred to the Scottish Government on the establishment of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office of the Advocate General for Scotland should not be confused with that of "His Majesty's Advocate", which is the term used for the Lord Advocate in Scottish criminal proceedings.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] The first holder of the office was Lynda Clark, then Member of Parliament for Edinburgh Pentlands and from 2005 a member of the House of Lords as Baroness Clark of Calton.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 18 January 2006, Baroness Clark resigned to take up office as a Senator of the College of Justice, a judge of the Supreme Courts of Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office was then vacant until 15 March of that year when, under section 87 of the Scotland Act 1998, its functions were temporarily conferred on the Secretary of State for Scotland, Alistair Darling MP, himself a Scottish advocate.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] There had been substantial criticism from the judiciary and others of the length of time the office had been left vacant.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 21 March, however, it was announced Neil Davidson, former Solicitor General for Scotland, had been appointed Advocate General.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] He was created a life peer, as Baron Davidson of Glen Clova, on 22 March 2006.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 14 May 2010, Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness, a former Deputy First Minister of Scotland, was appointed by the coalition government.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] Richard Keen was appointed Advocate General in David Cameron's majority government on 29 May 2015, and has retained the post through two subsequent prime ministers to 2020.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] He was created a life peer, as Baron Keen of Elie, on 8 June 2015.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] He resigned on 16 September 2020 citing concerns arising from the UK Internal Market Bill, noting in his letter of resignation to Boris Johnson that he found it "increasingly difficult to reconcile what I consider to be my obligations as a Law Officer with your policy intentions".
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] Keith Stewart was appointed to succeed Keen on 15 October 2020.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] Catherine Smith was appointed to the office and a life peerage by the Starmer government on 29 August 2024.
[src:davidian-revolution/advocate-general-for-scotland] All staff are on secondment or loan from other government organisations, mainly the Scottish Government and the Ministry of Justice.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights and made land more productive.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open-field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for oats.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] New monastic orders such as the Cistercians became major landholders and sheep farmers, particularly in the Borders where they were organised in granges.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the late Medieval period, most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, known as husbandmen.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised for meat.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The rural economy appears to have boomed in the thirteenth century and in the immediate aftermath of the Black Death was still buoyant, but by the 1360s there was a severe falling off in incomes to be followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is roughly half the size of England and Wales and has approximately the same amount of coastline, but only between a fifth and a sixth of the amount of the arable or good pastoral land, under 60 metres above sea level, and most of this is located in the south and east.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This made marginal pastoral farming and fishing, the key factors in the pre-modern economy.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Its east Atlantic position means that it has moderate rainfall: today about 700 mm per year in the east and over 1,000 mm in the west.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This encouraged the spread of blanket peat bog, the acidity of which, combined with high level of wind and salt spray, made most of the western islands treeless.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The existence of hills, mountains, quicksands and marshes made agriculture and internal communication difficult.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The early Middle Ages, from the fifth century to the tenth century, were a period of climate deterioration, with a drop in temperature and an increase in rainfall, resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] With a lack of significant transport links and wider markets, most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than wheat.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The evidence of bones indicates that cattle were by far the most important domesticated animal, followed by pigs, sheep and goats, while domesticated fowl were very rare.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Christian missionaries from Ireland may have changed agricultural practice, bringing innovations such as the horizontal watermill and mould board ploughs, which were more effective in turning the soil.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters of the Medieval Warm Period allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas in the south and east than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The feudalism introduced under David I, particularly in the east and south where the crown's authority was greatest, saw the placement of baronial lordships.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Land was now held from the king, or a superior lord, in exchange for loyalty and forms of service that were usually military.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Barons, who held feudal tenures, had the right to hold baronial courts, which could deal with matters of land ownership.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the imposition of feudalism continued to sit beside the existing systems of landholding and tenure and it is not clear how this change impacted on the lives of the ordinary free and unfree workers.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In places, feudalism may have tied workers more closely to the land.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the predominantly pastoral nature of Scottish agriculture may have made the imposition of a manorial system, based on the English model, impracticable in some areas.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Obligations appear to have been limited to occasional labour service, seasonal renders of food, hospitality and money rents.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually included supplying oxen for ploughing the lord's land on an annual basis and the much resented obligation to grind corn at the lord's mill.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones, creating large tracts of land reserved for the leisure of the aristocracy and nobility.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were less rigorously enforced than in England, where the taking of wood and game were strictly forbidden, and all royal forests were on land already in the king's hands.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The introduction of new monastic orders such as the Cistercians in this period also brought innovations in agriculture.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Particularly in the Borders, their monasteries became major landholders, sheep farmers and producers of wool for the markets in Flanders.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were organised in granges, monastic farms run by lay brothers of the order.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Granges were theoretically within 30 miles of the mother monastery, so that those working there could return for services on Sundays and feast days.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were used for variety of purposes, including pastoral, arable and industrial production.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, to manage more distant assets in Ayrshire, Melrose Abbey used Mauchline as a "super grange", to oversee lesser granges.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Some abbeys like Melrose had at least 12,000 sheep in the late thirteenth century.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This expanded from the use of small enclosed fields, which continued from the prehistoric era.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The infield was the best land, close to housing.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was farmed continuously and most intensively, receiving most of the manure.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were usually bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for largely for oats.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was fertilised from the overnight folding of cattle in the summer and was often left fallow to recover its fertility.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In fertile regions the infield could be extensive, but in the uplands it might be small, surrounded by large amounts of outfield.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In coastal areas fertiliser included seaweed and around the major burghs urban refuse was used.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Yields were fairly low, often around three times the quantity of seed sown, although they could reach twice that yield on some infields.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The main unit of land measurement in Scotland was the *davoch* (i.e.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This unit is also known as the "Scottish ploughgate".
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In English-speaking Lothian, it was simply a ploughgate.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It may have measured about 104 acres (0.42 km2), divided into 4 *raths* or eight *oxgangs*, the area that eight oxen were said to be able to plough in one year.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the fourteenth century most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, who were usually known as husbandmen or bonders.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The average amount of land used by a husbandman in Scotland, known as a husbandland, was 26 acres, or 2 oxgangs.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They would also have had a share of hay meadow and common pasture.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Below the husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants, were the cottars, who often shared rights to common pasture, occupied small portions of land and participated in joint farming as hired labour.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Farms also might have grassmen, who had rights only to grazing.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Pasture was often accessed by shieling-grounds, with shelters made of stone or turf, used for the grazing of cattle in summer.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These would often be distant from the main settlements in the Lowlands, but might be relatively close in the more remote Highlands.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs, were a ridge and furrow pattern, similar to that used in parts of England, with alternating "runs" (furrows) and "rigs" (ridges).
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land, helping to offset some of the problems of extreme weather conditions.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective on heavy soils and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were usually pulled by a team of eight oxen, which would have taken four men to operate and only covered half an acre a day.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Key crops included kale (for both humans and animals), and hemp and flax for cloth production.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised primarily for meat.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This was followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Towards the end of the period average temperatures began to reduce again, with the cooler and wetter conditions of the Little Ice Age limiting the extent of arable agriculture, particularly in the Highlands.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The early modern era saw the impact of the Little Ice Age, which peaked towards the end of the seventeenth century.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The closing decade of the seventeenth century saw a slump, followed by four years of failed harvests, in what is known as the "seven ill years", but these shortages would be the last of their kind.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] After the Union of 1707 there was a conscious attempt to improve agriculture among the gentry and nobility.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Introductions included haymaking, the English plough, new crops, crop rotation and encloses were introduced.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The resulting Lowland Clearances saw hundreds of thousands of cottars and tenant farmers from central and southern Scotland lose access to land and either become landless agricultural workers or emigrate to the growing industrial cities or elsewhere.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The later Highland Clearances involved the eviction of many traditional tenants as lands were enclosed, principally for sheep farming.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In the first phase, many Highlanders were relocated as crofters, living on very small rented farms which required other employment to be found.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In the twentieth century Scottish agriculture became more susceptible to world markets.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] There were dramatic price rises in the First World War, but a slump in the 1920s and 1930s, followed by more rises in World War II.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In 1947 annual price reviews were introduced in an attempt to stabilise the market.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] There was a drive in UK agriculture to greater production until the late 1970s, resulting in intensive farming.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] There was increasing mechanisation and farming became less labour-intensive.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] UK membership of the European Economic Community from 1972 began a change in orientation for Scottish farming.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Some sectors became viable only with subsidies.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] A series of reforms to the CAP from the 1990s attempted to control over-production, limit incentives for intensive farming and mitigate environmental damage.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] A dual farm structure has emerged with agriculture divided between large commercial farms and small pluralised and diversified holdings.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Roughly 79 per cent of Scotland’s total land area is under agricultural production.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Cereals accounted for 78 per cent of cropped land area (not total farmed area), while livestock numbers have been falling in recent years.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Around 15 per cent of the total land area of Scotland is forested, most in public ownership controlled by the Forestry Commission.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Total income from farming has been rising since the turn of the millennium.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Aquaculture production is focused on the West and North of the country.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Some farm businesses rely on sources of income other than from farming.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Scottish agriculture employs around 1.5 per cent of the workforce and contributes to around 1 per cent of the Scottish economy.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The defining factor in the geography of Scotland is the distinction between the Highlands and Islands in the north and west and the Lowlands in the south and east.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The Highlands are further divided into the Northwest Highlands and the Grampian Mountains by the fault line of the Great Glen.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The Lowlands are divided into the fertile belt of the Central Lowlands and the higher terrain of the Southern Uplands, which included the Cheviot Hills, over which the border with England runs.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The Central Lowland belt averages about 50 miles in width, and contains most of the good quality agricultural land.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland is half the size of England and Wales in area, but with its many inlets, islands and inland lochs, it has roughly the same amount of coastline at 4,000 miles.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Only a fifth of Scotland is less than 60 metres above sea level.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland's soils are diverse for a relatively small country due to the variation in geology, topography, climate, altitude and land use history.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] There are very productive arable soils in the east of the country, including some of the most productive for wheat and barley of anywhere in the world.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland's soils differ from much of the rest of the UK and Europe and they provide valuable habitats for wildlife and flora.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] They are largely naturally acidic in nature with high concentrations of organic carbon.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] They are predominantly coarse textured and often exhibit poor drainage.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The climate of Scotland is temperate and very changeable, but rarely extreme.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland is warmed by the North Atlantic Drift and given the northerly location of the country, experiences much milder conditions than areas on similar latitudes.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Average temperatures are lower than in the rest of Great Britain.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Western coastal areas of Scotland are warmer than the east and inland areas, due to the influence of the Atlantic currents, and the colder surface temperatures of the North Sea.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Rainfall totals vary widely across Scotland—the western highlands of Scotland are one of the wettest places in the UK with annual rainfall up to 4,577 mm (180.2 in).
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In comparison, much of eastern Scotland receives less than 870 mm (34.3 in) annually; lying in the rain shadow of the western uplands.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Annual average sunshine totals vary from as little as 711–1140 hours in the Highlands and the north-west up to 1471–1540 hours on the extreme eastern and south-western coasts.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Wind prevails from the south-west, bringing warm, wet and unstable air from the Atlantic.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The windiest areas of Scotland are in the north and west, with parts of the Outer Hebrides, Orkney and Shetland experiencing over 30 days with gales per year.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Vigorous Atlantic depressions, also known as European windstorms, are a common feature of the autumn and winter in Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Mesolithic hunter-gatherer encampments formed the first known settlements in Scotland around 8500 BCE.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] These were highly mobile boat-using people making tools from bone, stone and antlers.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In the Neolithic period, around 6,000 years ago, there is evidence of permanent settlements and farming.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Archaeological evidence indicates that the two main sources of food were grain and cow's milk.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] From the beginning of the Bronze Age, about 2000 BCE, arable land spread at the expense of forest.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] From the Iron Age, beginning in the seventh century BCE, there is evidence of hill forts in southern Scotland that are associated with cultivation ridges and terraces.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Souterrains, small underground constructions, may have been for storing perishable agricultural products.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Aerial photography reveals extensive prehistoric field systems that underlie existing boundaries in some Lowland areas, suggesting that the fertile plains were already densely exploited for agriculture.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] During the period of Roman occupation there was re-growth of birch, oak and hazel for five centuries, suggesting a decline of population and agriculture.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The early Middle Ages were a period of climate deterioration resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Farming was based around a single homestead or a small cluster of three or four homes, each probably containing a nuclear family.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than corn (here meaning wheat) and cattle were the most important domesticated animal.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] As feudal distinctions declined in the early modern era, the barons and tenants-in-chief merged to form a new identifiable group, the lairds.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] With the substantial landholders of the yeomen, these heritors were the major landholding orders.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Those with property rights included husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Many young people, both male and female, left home to become domestic and agricultural servants.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The early modern era also saw the impact of the Little Ice Age, of colder and wetter weather, which peaked towards the end of the seventeenth century.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Almost half the years in the second half of the sixteenth century saw local or national scarcity, necessitating the shipping of large quantities of grain from the Baltic.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In the early seventeenth century famine was relatively common, with four periods of famine prices between 1620 and 1625.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The English invasions of the 1640s had a profound impact on the Scottish economy.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Under the Commonwealth, the country was relatively highly taxed, but gained access to English markets.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] After the Restoration the formal frontier with England was re-established, along with its customs duties.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Economic conditions were generally favourable from 1660 to 1688, as land owners promoted better tillage and cattle-raising.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The closing decade of the seventeenth century there was a slump in trade with the Baltic and France and changes in the Scottish cattle trade, followed by four years of failed harvests (1695, 1696 and 1698-9), known as the "seven ill years".
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The shortages of the 1690s would be the last of their kind.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Increasing contacts with England after the Union of 1707 led to a conscious attempt to improve agriculture among the gentry and nobility.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The English plough was introduced and foreign grasses, the sowing of rye grass and clover.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Turnips and cabbages were introduced, lands enclosed and marshes drained, lime was put down to combat soil acidity, roads built and woods planted.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Drilling and sowing and crop rotation were introduced.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The introduction of the potato to Scotland in 1739 provided a crop with a high yield, producing 3 to 5 times more calories per acre than a cereal crop.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Enclosures began to displace the run rig system.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The first result of these changes were the Lowland Clearances.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The botanist John Hope complained about British naturalists who were enthusiastically exploring the landscape of colonial America while "absolutely inattentive to the natural productions of our native country".
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] He founded the Society for the Importation of Foreign Seeds and Plants pursuing, as Carl Linnaeus did in Lapland, the adaptation of valuable cash crop plants to the Highlands.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Agricultural improvement spread north and west, mostly over the period 1760 to 1850 as the Highland Clearances.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Many farming tenants were evicted and offered tenancies in crofting communities, with their former possessions converted into large-scale sheep farms.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Crofts were intended to be too small to support the occupants, so forcing them to work in other industries, such as fishing, quarrying or kelping.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In the 1840 and 1850s Scotland suffered its last major subsistence crisis, when the potato blight that caused the Great Famine of Ireland reached the Highlands in 1846.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] This gave rise to the second phase of the Highland clearances, when landlords provided assisted passages for their tenants to emigrate in a desperate effort to rid themselves of a redundant population that was dependent on famine relief.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In the twentieth century Scottish agriculture became susceptible to the ups and downs of world markets.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] After World War II there was a drive in UK agriculture to greater production until the late 1970s, resulting in intensive farming.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] More areas of marginal land were brought into production.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] There was increasing mechanisation of Scottish agriculture and farming became less labour-intensive.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The UK membership of the European Economic Community (later the European Union) in 1972 began a change in orientation for Scottish farming.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Some sectors, particularly hill sheep farming, became viable only with subsidies.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] A dual farm structure emerged, with agriculture divided between large commercial farms and small pluralised and diversified holdings.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] At the time of the June 2013 agricultural census the total area of agricultural holdings in Scotland was 5.6 million hectares, equal to 73 per cent of Scotland’s total land area.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Just over half of this was rough grazing, with about a quarter taken up by grass, and about ten per cent used for crops or left fallow.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The remainder was made up of woodland, ponds, yards or other uses.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] There was a further 580,000 hectares of common grazing, which if included made the total area 6.2 million hectares, or 79 per cent of Scotland’s total land area.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Because of the persistence of feudalism and the land enclosures of the nineteenth century, the ownership of most land is concentrated in relatively few hands (some 350 people own about half the land).
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] As a result, in 2003 the Scottish Parliament passed Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 that empowered tenant farmers and communities to purchase land even if the landlord did not want to sell.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In June 2013, of crops grown in Scotland (excluding grass), cereals accounted for 78 per cent of the land area, with nearly three-quarters of that being barley (340,000 hectares).
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Wheat was also significant (87,000 hectares), along with oilseed rape (34,000 hectares), oats (32,000 hectares) and potatoes (29,000 hectares).
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Amongst fruit and vegetables, a total of 911 hectares of strawberries were grown, mainly under cover, which was the largest source of income amongst horticulture crops.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The major areas of cereal production were Grampian, Tayside, Borders, Lothian and Fife.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Livestock numbers have been falling in recent years.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The trend began at the turn of the millennium in the case of pigs and sheep and dates to the mid-1970s in the case of cattle.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In June 2013 there were 6.6 million sheep, 1.8 million cattle and 308,000 pigs, the lowest numbers since the 1940 and 1950s.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Poultry numbers have tended to fluctuate over the last 25 years, but were down to 14.2 million in 2013.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] About 13,340 km2 of land in Scotland is forested representing around 15 per cent of the total land area of Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The majority of forests are in public ownership, with forestry policy being controlled by the Forestry Commission.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The biggest plantations and timber resources are to be found in Dumfries and Galloway, Tayside, Argyll and the area governed by Highland Council.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The economic activities generated by forestry in Scotland include planting and harvesting as well as sawmilling, the production of pulp and paper and the manufacture of higher value goods.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Forests, especially those surrounding populated areas in Central Scotland also provide a recreation resource.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Total income from farming (TIFF) has been rising since the turn of the millennium.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] It was estimated at £700 million in 2012, being made up of £2.9 billion in outputs and £570 million in support payments, offset by £2.8 billion in costs.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The initial estimate of TIFF for 2013 was £830 million, an increase largely linked to the improved weather.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] TIFF per annual work unit increased to £31,000, similar to the value in 2011.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The total output of aquaculture was estimated in 2011 at around £434 million per year, including around £412 million for farmed Atlantic salmon, £14.34 million for rainbow trout and £7.7 million for shellfish.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Brown trout, sea trout, halibut and Arctic charr are also farmed in Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Some farm businesses rely on sources of income other than from farming, including contracting work, hosting mobile phone masts, tourism and recreation and financial support from grants and subsidies.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Analysis of the Farm Accounts Survey suggests that, excluding support from grants and subsidies, the average farm made a loss of £16,000 in 2012.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] However, calculations from TIFF suggest that, excluding support, the sector still made a small profit.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Government figures indicate that in 2013 Scottish agriculture employed around 1.5 per cent of the workforce and contributes around 1 per cent of the Scottish economy.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In the Highlands and Islands, around 10 per cent of the workforce are engaged in agriculture and livestock products contribute around 70 per cent of the output.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The West of Scotland Agricultural College formed in 1899, the East of Scotland Agricultural College in 1901, and the North of Scotland Agricultural College in 1904; these colleges amalgamated to form the Scottish Agricultural College in 1990.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Site-specific nature conservations began in the UK with the creation of the Nature Conservancy in 1948, which later became the Nature Conservancy Council (NCC).
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] It moved from a research-based advisory group to become a campaigning body.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The 1949 National Parks and Access to the Countryside Act excluded Scotland, but introduced the concept of Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI), which were to become a key part of managing nature conservation.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] A Countryside Commission Scotland (CSS) was established under the Countryside Scotland Act, 1967.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The NCC was broken up in 1991 and in Scotland was merged with CSS to produce Scottish Natural Heritage (SNH), under a UK-wide Joint Nature Conservation Committee.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] SNH has a remit for both land and nature conservation and a responsibility towards sustainability and to the consideration of the needs of the Scottish people.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] In Scotland, a right of way is a route over which the public has been able to pass unhindered for at least 20 years.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The route must link two "public places", such as villages, churches or roads.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Unlike in England and Wales there is no obligation on Scottish local authorities to signpost or mark a right of way.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] However, the charity Scotways, formed in 1845 to protect rights of way, records and signs the routes.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] The Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 gives everyone statutory access rights to most land and inland water in Scotland, to non-motorized traffic, making the existence of rights of way less important in terms of access to land in Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/agriculture-in-scotland] Certain categories of land are excluded from this presumption of open access, such as railway land, airfields and private gardens.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred was born in Hexham, Northumbria, in 1110, one of three sons of Eilaf, priest of St Andrew's at Hexham, himself a son of another Eilaf, treasurer of Durham.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In 1095, the Council of Claremont had forbidden the ordination of the sons of priests.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] This was done in part to end the inheritance of benefices.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] He may have been partially educated by Lawrence of Durham, who sent him a hagiography of Saint Brigid.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred's early education was probably at the cathedral school at Durham.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred spent several years at the court of King David I of Scotland in Roxburgh, possibly from the age of 14, rising to the rank of *echonomus* (often translated "steward" or "Master of the Household").
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] At some point during this period, Aelred became the target of personal harassment by a knight of the king's court, which came to a head in the king's presence and included a degrading sexual slur.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In 1138, when Rievaulx's patron, Walter Espec, was to surrender his Wark on Tweed Castle to King David of Scotland, Aelred reportedly accompanied Abbot William of Rievaulx to the Scottish border to negotiate the transfer.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] He saw that his reluctance to part from his friends at court delayed his adopting his monastic calling.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] For Aelred, the source and object of true friendship is Christ.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In 1142 Aelred travelled to Rome, alongside Walter of London, Archdeacon of York, to represent before Pope Innocent II the northern prelates who opposed the election of Henry de Sully, nephew of King Stephen as archbishop of York.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] The result of the journey was that Aelred brought back a letter from Pope Innocent summoning the superiors whom Aelred represented to appear in Rome the following March to make their deposition in the required canonical form.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] The resulting negotiations dragged on for many years.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Upon his return from Rome, Aelred became novice master at Rievaulx.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In 1143, he was appointed abbot of the new Revesby Abbey, a daughter house of Rievaulx in Lincolnshire.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In 1147, he was elected abbot of Rievaulx itself, a position he was to hold until his death.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Under his administration, the abbey is said to have grown to some 140 monks and 500 *conversi* and laymen.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] His role as abbot required him to travel.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Cistercian abbots were expected to make annual visitations to daughter-houses, and Rievaulx had five in England and Scotland by the time Aelred held office.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Moreover, Aelred had to make the long sea journey to the annual general chapter of the Order at Cîteaux in France.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Alongside his role as a monk and later abbot, Aelred was involved throughout his life in political affairs.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] The fourteenth-century version of the *Peterborough Chronicle* states that Aelred's efforts during the twelfth-century papal schism brought about Henry II's decisive support for the Cistercian candidate, resulting in 1161 in the formal recognition of Pope Alexander III.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred wrote several influential books on spirituality, among them *Speculum caritatis* ("The Mirror of Charity," reportedly written at the request of Bernard of Clairvaux) and *De spirituali amicitiâ* ("On Spiritual Friendship").
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] He also wrote seven works of history, addressing three of them to Henry II of England, advising him how to be a good king and declaring him to be the true descendant of Anglo-Saxon kings.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In his later years, he is thought to have suffered from the kidney stones and arthritis.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Walter reports that in 1157 the Cistercian General Council allowed him to sleep and eat in Rievaulx's infirmary; later he lived in a nearby building constructed for him.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred died in the winter of 1166–67, probably on 12 January 1167 at Rievaulx.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] It was likely at Durham that Aelred first encountered Cicero's *Laelius de Amicitia*.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In Roman terminology *amicitia* means "friendship" and could be between states or individuals.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] It suggested an equality of status and in practice it might only be an alliance to pursue mutual interests.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] For Cicero, *amicitia* involved genuine trust and affection.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] "But I must at the very beginning lay down this principle —friendship can only exist between good men.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In *Confessions*, Augustine of Hippo identifies three phases of friendship: adolescence, early adulthood and adulthood.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Adolescent friendships are essentially self-interested comradeship.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Augustine then describes a close friendship he had as a young adult with a colleague.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] This was based on love and grew out of shared interests and experiences and what each learned from the other.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] The third mature phase for Augustine is transcendent, in that he loves others "in Christ": the focus is on Christ and the point of friendship is to grow closer to Christ with and through friends.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred was greatly influenced by Cicero, but later modified his interpretation upon reading Augustine of Hippo's *Confessions*.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In *De spirituali amicitiâ*, Aelred adopted Cicero's dialogue format.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In the Prologue however, he mirrors Augustine's description of his early adolescence with the speaker describing his time at school, where "the charm of my companions gave me the greatest pleasure.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Among the usual faults that often endanger youth, my mind surrendered wholly to affection and became devoted to love.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Jocelyn of Furness, writing about Aelred after his death, described him as "a man of the highest integrity, of great practical wisdom, witty and eloquent, a pleasant companion, generous and discreet.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] And with all these qualities, he exceeded all his fellow prelates of the Church in his patience and tenderness.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred was never formally canonised in the manner that was later established, but he became the centre of a cult in the north of England that was officially recognised by Cistercians in 1476.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] As such, he was venerated as a saint, with his body kept at Rievaulx.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In the sixteenth century, before the dissolution of the monastery, John Leland, claims he saw Aelred's shrine at Rievaulx containing Aelred's body glittering with gold and silver.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Today, Aelred of Rievaulx is commemorated as a saint on 12 January, the traditional date of his death, in the latest official edition of the Roman Martyrology, which expresses the official position of the Catholic Church.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] He also appears in the calendars of various other Christian denominations.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Much of Aelred's history is known because of the *Life* written about him by Walter Daniel shortly after his death.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred is remembered in the Church of England with a Lesser Festival and on the Episcopal Church calendar with a feast on 12 January.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred has been popular with small circles of gay Catholics since at least the 1970s, and during the same time period, Brian Patrick McGuire and his students discussed the possibility that Aelred might have possessed a homosexual orientation.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In 1980, the historian John Boswell characterized Aelred as a gay man in *Christianity, Social Tolerance, and Homosexuality,* the landmark study into the relationship between the medieval Church and homosexuality.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] In modern times, several gay-friendly organizations have adopted Aelred as their patron saint, including Integrity USA in the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, and the Order of St.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred's inclusion on the calendar of the Episcopal Church was initiated by Integrity USA in 1985, and he was approved by the House of Bishops with their full awareness that he was believed to be a gay man by Integrity.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Elizabeth Freeman has argued that discussion of his alleged homosexuality has abounded atop misunderstandings of monastic language and mistaking his interest in Christian friendship for homosexuality.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred also refers directly to the relationship of Jesus and John the Apostle as a "marriage", which is aligned with Cistercian emphasis upon the Song of Songs, and the symbolism of love between man and God, expressed through a predominantly Virgilian and Ovidian topos.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Aelred called this "marriage" an 'organ of experience', with nothing to do with romantic or sexual reality which were believed to be fundamentally contrary to monastic life.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] Julia Kristeva argues that this is reflected much more accurately by the concept of 'imaginatio' than 'amor' (romantic love): "It constituted the intimate link between being and the world, through which the person may assimilate the exterior world while also defining the self as a subject".
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] McGuire notes that "in the *Life of Waldef*, there is a colorful story about how a woman tried to tempt the budding Cistercian saint into bed, and how he resisted her.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] For his efforts in writing and administration Aelred was called by David Knowles the "St.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] All of Aelred's works have appeared in translation, most in English and in French; the remaining three volumes of his sermons are being translated into English and will appear from Cistercian Publications in 2018–2020.
[src:davidian-revolution/ailred-of-rievaulx] There are already available in French in a five-volume edition.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The **Davidian Revolution** is a name given by many scholars to the changes which took place in the Kingdom of Scotland during the reign of David I (1124–1153).
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] These included his foundation of burghs, implementation of the ideals of Gregorian Reform, foundation of monasteries, Normanisation of the Scottish government, and the introduction of feudalism through immigrant Norman and Anglo-Norman knights, as well as Flemish settlers.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] King David I is still widely regarded as one of the most significant rulers in Scotland's history.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The reason is what Barrow and Lynch both call the "Davidian Revolution".
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David's "revolution" is held to underpin the development of later medieval Scotland, whereby the changes that he inaugurated grew into most of the central non-native institutions of the later medieval kingdom.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The central idea is that from the late 10th century onwards the culture and institutions of the old Carolingian heartlands in northern France and western Germany spread to outlying areas, creating a more recognisable "Europe".
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] In this model, the old Carolingian Empire formed a "core" and the outlying areas a "periphery".
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The Norman conquest of England in the years after 1066 is considered to have made England more like if not part of this "core".
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] After David's reign, it had gained all of these.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Yet, David's life as a "reformer" also has a context in the Gaelic-speaking world.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] This is particularly true in understanding David's enthusiasm for the Gregorian Reform.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The latter was a revolutionary movement within the western church spearheaded vigorously in the papacy of Pope Gregory VII which sought renewed spiritual rigour, ecclesiastical discipline and doctrinal obedience to the papacy and its sponsored theologians.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The Normans who came to England adopted this ideology, and soon began attacking the Scottish and Irish Gaelic world as spiritually backward – a mindset which even underlay the hagiography of David's mother Margaret, written by her confessor Thurgot at the instigation of the English royal court.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Yet up until this period, Gaelic monks (often called *Céli Dé*) from Ireland and Scotland had been pioneering their own kind of ascetic reform both in Great Britain and in continental Europe, where they founded many of their own monastic houses.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Since the end of the 11th century various Gaelic princes had themselves been attempting to accommodate Gregorian reform, examples being Muirchertach Ua Briain, Toirdelbach Ua Conchobair, and Edgar and Alexander I of Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Indeed, the Gaelic world had never been closed off from its neighbours in England or continental Europe.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Gaelic warriors and holy men had been travelling regularly through England and the continent for centuries.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David's predecessor Macbeth (King, 1040–57) had employed Norman mercenaries even before the conquest of England, and English exiles after the conquest fled to the courts of both Máel Coluim III, King of Scotland, and Toirdelbach Ua Briain, High King of Ireland.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] During this period, Scotland experienced innovations in governmental practices and the importation of foreign, generally French, knights.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] It is to David's reign that the beginnings of Scottish feudalism and seignorialism are generally assigned.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Geoffrey Barrow wrote that David's reign witnessed "a revolution in Scots dynastic law" as well as "fundamental innovations in military organization" and "in the composition and dominant characteristics of its ruling class".
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] This is defined as "castle-building, the regular use of professional cavalry, the knight's fee" as well as "homage and fealty".
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David established large scale feudal lordships in the west of his Cumbrian principality for the leading members of the French military entourage who kept him in power.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Additionally, many smaller-scale feudal lordships were created.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The latter's name occurs in a charter by David's grandson King William to Freskin's son, William, granting Strathbrock in West Lothian and Duffus, Kintrae, and other lands in Moray, "which his father held in the time of King David".
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The name Freskin is Flemish, and in the words of Geoffrey Barrow "it is virtually certain that Freskin belonged to a large group of Flemish settlers who came to Scotland in the middle decades of the 12th century and were chiefly to be found in West Lothian and the valley of the Clyde".
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Freskin was responsible for building a castle in the distant territory of Moray, and because Freskin had no kinship ties to the locality, his position was dependent entirely on the king, thus bringing the territory more firmly under royal control.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Freskin's land acquisition does not appear to be unique, and may have been part of a royal policy in the aftermath of the defeat of king Óengus of Moray.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Steps were taken during David's reigns to make the government of Scotland, or that part of Scotland that he administered, more like the government of Anglo-Norman England.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] New sheriffdoms enabled the King to effectively administer royal demesne land.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] During David I's reign, royal sheriffs had been established in the king's core personal territories; namely, in rough chronological order, at Roxburgh, Scone, Berwick-upon-Tweed, Stirling and Perth.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The Justiciarship too was created in David's reign.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Two Justiciarships were created, one for Scotland-proper and one for Lothian, i.e. for Scotland north of the river Forth and Scotland south of the Forth and east of Galloway.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Although this institution had Anglo-Norman origins, in Scotland north of the Forth at least it represented some form of continuity with an older office.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] For instance, Mormaer Causantín of Fife is styled *judex magnus* (i.e. great Brehon); the Justiciarship of Scotia hence was just as much a Gaelic office modified by Normanisation as it was an import, illustrating Barrow's "balance of New and Old" argument.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] An important source of David's wealth during his career came from the revenue of his English earldom and the proceeds of the silver mines at Alston.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Alston silver allowed David to indulge in the "regalian gratification" of his own coinage and to continue his project of attempting to link royal power and economic expansion.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Building programmes depended to a large degree on disposable income; consumption of foreign and exotic commodities broadened; men of ability and ambition found their way to court and entered the service of the king.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] What is more, no less than the written word, the coin acted upon the culture and mental categories of people who made use of it.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Like a seal displaying the king in majesty, the coin broadcast the image of the ruler to his people and, more fundamentally, altered the simple nature of trade.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Though coins were not absent from Scotland before David, these were by definition foreign objects, unseen and unused by most of the population.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The arrival of a native coinage – no less than the arrival of towns, laws and charters – marked the penetration of the "Europeanising" concepts of European culture into ever less "non-European" Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] In part, he made use of the "English" income secured for him by his marriage to Matilda de Senlis in order to finance the construction of the first true towns in Scotland, and these, in turn, allowed the establishment of several more.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] As Prince of the Cumbrians, David founded the first two burghs of "Scotland", at Roxburgh and Berwick.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] These were settlements with defined boundaries and guaranteed trading rights, locations where the king could collect and sell the products of his *cain* and *conveth* (a payment made *in lieu* of providing the king hospitality) rendered to him.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] These burghs were essentially Scotland's first towns.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David would found more of these burghs when he became King of Scots.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Before 1135, David laid the foundations of four more burghs, this time in the new territory he had acquired as King of Scots; burghs were founded at Stirling, Dunfermline and Edinburgh, three of David's favoured residences.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Around 15 burghs have their foundations traced to the reign of David I, although because of the sparsity of some of the evidence, this exact number is uncertain.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Perhaps nothing in David's reign compares in importance to this.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] No institution would do more to reshape the long-term economic and ethnic shape of Scotland than the burgh.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The thesis that the "rise of towns" was indirectly responsible for the medieval flourishing of Europe has been accepted, at least in a circumscribed form, from the time of Henri Pirenne, a century ago.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Commerce generated by and the economic privileges granted to merchant towns across northern Europe in the eleventh and twelfth centuries paid for, in new revenues, the increasing diversification of society and ensured that further growth would occur.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] What was of great importance for the future of Scotland was the creation by David of perhaps seven such jurisdictionally licensed communities at ancient royal centres and even at new sites, the latter mainly along his eastern seaboard.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The changes that David was most noted for at the time, however, were his religious changes.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The reason for this is that practically all our sources were Reform-minded monks or clerics, grateful to David for his efforts.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David's changes, or alleged changes, can be divided into two parts: monastic patronage and ecclesiastical restructuring.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David was certainly at least one of medieval Scotland's greatest monastic patrons.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] In 1113, in perhaps David's first act as Prince of the Cumbrians, he founded Selkirk Abbey for the Tironensian Order.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Several years later, perhaps in 1116, David visited Tiron itself, probably to acquire more monks; in 1128 he transferred Selkirk Abbey to Kelso, nearer Roxburgh, at this point his chief residence.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] In 1144, David and Bishop John of Glasgow prompted Kelso Abbey to found a daughter house, Lesmahagow Priory.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David also continued his predecessor Alexander's patronage of the Augustinians, founding Holyrood Abbey with monks from Merton Priory.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David and Bishop John, moreover, established Jedburgh Abbey with canons from Beauvais in 1138.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] However, by 23 March 1137 David had also turned his patronage towards the Cistercian Order, founding the famous Melrose Abbey from monks of Rievaulx.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Melrose would become the greatest medieval monastic establishment in Scotland south of the river Forth.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] It was from Melrose that David established Newbattle Abbey in Midlothian, Kinloss Abbey in Moray, and Holmcultram Abbey in Cumberland.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David also, like Alexander, patronised Benedictines, introducing monks to Coldingham (a non-monastic property of Durham Priory) in 1139 and having made it a priory by 1149.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David's activities were paralleled by other "Scottish" magnates.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] For instance, the Premonstratensian house of Dryburgh Abbey was founded in 1150 by monks from Alnwick Abbey with the patronage of Hugh de Morville, Lord of Lauderdale.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Moreover, six years after the foundation of Melrose Abbey, King Fergus of Galloway likewise founded a Cistercian abbey from Rievaulx, Dundrennan Abbey, which would become a powerful landowner in both Galloway and Ireland and was known to Francesco Pegolotti as Scotland's richest abbey.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Not only were such monasteries an expression of David's undoubted piety, but they also functioned to transform Scottish society.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Monasteries became centres of foreign influence, being founded by French or English monks.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] They provided sources of literate men, able to serve the crown's growing administrative needs.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] This was particularly the case with the Augustinians.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Moreover, these new monasteries, and the Cistercian ones in particular, introduced new agricultural practices.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] In the words of one historian, the Cistercians were "pioneers or frontiersmen ... cultural revolutionaries, who carried new techniques of land management and new attitudes towards land exploitation".
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Duncan calls Scotland's new Cistercian establishments "the largest and most significant contribution by David I to the religious life of the kingdom".
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Cistercians equated spiritual health with economic achievement and environmental exploitation.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Cistercian labour transformed southern Scotland into one of northern Europe's main sources of sheep wool.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Almost as soon as he was in charge of the Cumbrian principality, David placed the bishopric of Glasgow under his chaplain, John, whom David may have met for the first time during his participation in Henry's conquest of Normandy after 1106.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] John himself was closely associated with the Tironensian Order, and presumably committed to the new Gregorian ideas regarding episcopal organisation.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David carried out an inquest, afterwards assigned to the bishopric all the lands of his principality, except those in the east of his principality which were already governed by the Scotland proper-based bishop of St Andrews.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David was responsible for assigning to Glasgow enough lands directly to make the bishopric self-sufficient and for ensuring that in the longer term Glasgow would become the second most important bishopric in the Kingdom of Scotland.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] By the 1120s, work also began on building a proper cathedral for the diocese.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] David would also try to ensure that his reinvigorated episcopal see would retain independence from other bishoprics, an aspiration which would generate a great deal of tension with the English church, where both the Archbishop of Canterbury and the Archbishop of York claimed overlordship.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] It was once held that Scotland's episcopal sees and entire parochial system owed their origins to the innovations of David I.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Today, scholars have moderated this view.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] Although David moved the bishopric of Mortlach east to his new burgh of Aberdeen, and arranged the creation of the diocese of Caithness, no other bishoprics can be safely called David's creation.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] The bishopric of Glasgow was restored rather than resurrected.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] In the case of the Bishop of Whithorn, the resurrection of that see was the work of Thurstan, Archbishop of York, with King Fergus of Galloway and the cleric Gille Aldan.
[src:davidian-revolution/davidian-revolution] As for the development of the parochial system, David's traditional role as its creator can not be sustained.
